"""
MKT Christ Commentary — 1 Kings chapters 18–19
Run: python3 scripts/zc-christ-1kings-18-19.py

Ch18: Mount Carmel — Elijah, fire, and the either/or of covenant allegiance
      Key types: divine fire → Pentecost; altar repair → temple cleansing;
      twelve stones → twelve tribes/disciples; Baal's silence → futility of idolatry
Ch19: Horeb theophany — still small voice, 40-day fast, Elisha's call
      Key types: angel provision → Matt 4:11; 40 days → Jesus's temptation;
      still small voice → Incarnation pattern; plow-burning → radical discipleship

Key typological connections:
- 18:17: 'troubler of Israel' → Luke 23:5 (Jesus 'stirs up the people')
- 18:21: wavering between two opinions → Matt 6:24; Jas 1:8
- 18:24: God who answers by fire → Acts 2:3 (Pentecost)
- 18:31: twelve stones → Matt 19:28; Rev 21:12 (twelve tribes reconstituted)
- 18:38: fire consumes all → Heb 12:29 (consuming fire)
- 18:39: 'The LORD, he is God' → Phil 2:11 (universal confession)
- 19:5-8: angel provision → Matt 4:11; 40 days → Matt 4:2
- 19:12: still small voice → Incarnation (Isa 53:2)
- 19:20: 'let me kiss my father goodbye' → Luke 9:61-62 (escalation in Christ)
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(layer, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    return json.loads(p.read_text()) if p.exists() else {}

def save_comm(layer, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / layer / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

CHRIST = {
  "18": {
    "1": "<p>After three years of the covenant curse — the drought announced in 17:1 — &ldquo;the word of the LORD came to Elijah: Go, present yourself to Ahab, and I will send rain.&rdquo; The structure is entirely YHWH&rsquo;s: the judgment is his, its duration is his, its lifting is his, and the prophet is the instrument of his word in both directions. Jas 5:17-18 uses this episode to demonstrate the efficacy of the &ldquo;prayer of a righteous person&rdquo; — Elijah &ldquo;prayed fervently that it might not rain, and for three years and six months it did not rain on the earth. Then he prayed again, and heaven gave rain.&rdquo; The drought and its ending are both answers to prayer. The three-year structure is typologically significant: the three days between Good Friday and Easter are the NT equivalent of a period of covenant darkness that YHWH himself resolves by sovereign word.</p>",
    "2": "<p>The famine is &ldquo;severe in Samaria&rdquo; — the judgment has reached maximum intensity at precisely the moment the word comes for restoration. YHWH&rsquo;s timing: he acts at the fullness of the crisis. The pattern recurs at the Incarnation: &ldquo;When the fullness of time had come, God sent forth his Son&rdquo; (Gal 4:4) — not before the crisis of the law&rsquo;s condemnation had been fully felt, but in its midst.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Obadiah is introduced as the palace administrator who &ldquo;greatly feared the LORD&rdquo; — a faithful man in a faithless court. His name means &ldquo;servant of YHWH.&rdquo; The presence of a God-fearer at the highest levels of Ahab&rsquo;s administration is a sign of the remnant principle: YHWH always maintains a witness even inside the most compromised structures. Joseph in Pharaoh&rsquo;s court, Daniel in Nebuchadnezzar&rsquo;s court, Obadiah in Ahab&rsquo;s court — the pattern of the faithful servant in the hostile institution.</p>",
    "4": "<p>When Jezebel was killing the LORD&rsquo;s prophets, Obadiah hid a hundred of them fifty to a cave, feeding them bread and water. The faithful administrator conceals the prophetic witness at personal risk; the caves become places of preservation. Rev 12:6 describes the woman &ldquo;fled into the wilderness, where she has a place prepared by God, in which she is to be nourished for 1,260 days&rdquo; — the same pattern of divine preservation of the prophetic witness through hidden means during the reign of the persecuting power. The hundredfold preservation (50 + 50) is not incidental: the gospel&rsquo;s promise of a &ldquo;hundredfold&rdquo; return (Matt 19:29) echoes this arithmetic of grace.</p>",
    "5": "<p>Ahab&rsquo;s concern during the famine is for his horses and mules — military assets that require fodder. The king searches the land for grass to preserve his war capability rather than seeking YHWH about the covenant breach that caused the famine. Matt 6:33: &ldquo;Seek first the kingdom of God and his righteousness, and all these things will be added to you.&rdquo; Ahab seeks the horses and cannot find the grass; the one who seeks YHWH first will find all provision. The inverted priority of the uncovenanted king.</p>",
    "6": "<p>The land is divided between Ahab and Obadiah for the search — each going alone, in opposite directions. The structural irony: the king and his faithful servant take different paths through the same land. Their encounter with Elijah shortly will reveal how different those paths are theologically, though they begin from the same point.</p>",
    "7": "<p>Obadiah meets Elijah &ldquo;on the road&rdquo; and falls on his face — the posture of worship before the man of God. Recognition of YHWH&rsquo;s prophet produces prostration even from a royal official. The disciples fell on their faces at the Transfiguration (Matt 17:6); the guards fell down at the resurrection (Matt 28:4). The appearance of the one who carries the divine word produces creaturely collapse.</p>",
    "8": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s command is simple: &ldquo;Go tell your master: Elijah is here.&rdquo; The prophet&rsquo;s self-announcement to a hostile king; the willingness to present himself to danger by the word of YHWH. Cf. John 18:5-6: when Jesus says &ldquo;I am he&rdquo; to the soldiers, they fall to the ground — the self-announcement of the one who carries divine authority has an inherent power.</p>",
    "9": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s question — &ldquo;What wrong have I done that you would hand your servant over to Ahab to be killed?&rdquo; — expresses the fear of those who serve the God-fearer within a hostile establishment. He has survived by hiddenness; being associated publicly with Elijah is potentially fatal. The tension between faithful concealment and courageous witness that runs through both Testaments.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Ahab has searched every nation and kingdom for Elijah and required them to swear they had not found him — the obsession of the covenant-breaking king with silencing the prophetic word. Persecution of the prophet is the tyrant&rsquo;s response to the word that exposes him. Jesus before Pilate: &ldquo;Herod and Pilate became friends with each other that very day&rdquo; (Luke 23:12) — political enemies unite against the prophet they cannot silence.</p>",
    "11": "<p>The difficulty of obeying the prophet&rsquo;s commission when the prophet himself may vanish. Obadiah understands that carrying Elijah&rsquo;s message to Ahab requires certainty that Elijah will still be there — otherwise Obadiah bears the cost of an undeliverable message. The messenger who bears the prophetic word must trust that the word itself will not abandon him.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;The Spirit of the LORD will carry you off to who knows where&rdquo; — Obadiah&rsquo;s description of Elijah as transported by the rûaḥ YHWH; he has seen this before. Acts 8:39: the Spirit &ldquo;carried Philip away&rdquo; after the baptism of the Ethiopian eunuch. The prophetic figure transported by the Spirit is a type of the ascended Christ who is &ldquo;taken up&rdquo; (Acts 1:9) and whose Spirit then moves freely where he wills (John 3:8).</p>",
    "13": "<p>Obadiah recounts what he did for the LORD&rsquo;s prophets — the testimony of his own faithfulness as grounds for the trust he requests. The appeal to covenant faithfulness as the basis for the relationship between the prophet and the God-fearing official. The NT equivalent: &ldquo;I have kept the faith&rdquo; (2 Tim 4:7) — Paul&rsquo;s appeal to his own record not as boasting but as grounds for the confidence that YHWH will deliver.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Obadiah&rsquo;s fear: &ldquo;He will kill me.&rdquo; The honest acknowledgment of the cost of prophetic obedience. The disciples shared this fear (John 20:19, locked doors &ldquo;for fear of the Jews&rdquo;). The prophetic commission always involves risk to the messenger; YHWH does not promise immunity from danger but presence through it.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;As the LORD of hosts lives, before whom I stand — I will certainly present myself to Ahab today.&rdquo; Elijah&rsquo;s oath uses two formulas: <em>YHWH ṣeḇāʾôt</em> (&ldquo;LORD of hosts&rdquo; — the cosmic warrior who commands the armies of heaven) and <em>ʾăšer ʿāmadtî lᵉpānāyw</em> (&ldquo;before whom I stand&rdquo; — the standing formula of the priestly and prophetic servant, cf. Jer 15:1; Zech 3:1). &ldquo;LORD of hosts&rdquo; is the name that governs military and cosmic conflict; Elijah invokes it precisely when presenting himself to the enemy. Rev 19:11-14: Christ as the warrior of the hosts appears at the eschatological showdown — the ultimate Carmel confrontation.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Obadiah obeys; Ahab goes to meet Elijah. The king moves toward the prophet — not the other way around. The reversal of expected power dynamics: YHWH&rsquo;s prophet does not come to court; the court comes to the prophet. The day is coming when &ldquo;kings shall shut their mouths because of him&rdquo; (Isa 52:15) — the final version of this reversal.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;Is that you, you troubler of Israel?&rdquo; — <em>ʿōkēr yiśrāʾēl</em>, &ldquo;disturber/troubler of Israel.&rdquo; The term was used of Achan (Josh 7:25; 1 Chr 2:7), who brought covenant disaster on Israel; Ahab applies it to the prophet who exposes covenant disaster. The establishment always accuses the prophetic witness of causing the trouble it merely names. Jesus was accused of &ldquo;stirring up the people&rdquo; (<em>anaseiō ton laon</em>, Luke 23:5); Paul&rsquo;s opponents called his group &ldquo;the ones who turn the world upside down&rdquo; (Acts 17:6). The prophet is always blamed for the disorder created by others&rsquo; unfaithfulness.</p>",
    "18": "<p>&ldquo;I have not troubled Israel — you and your father&rsquo;s house have, because you abandoned the commandments of the LORD and followed the Baals.&rdquo; The prophetic rebuttal of Ahab&rsquo;s accusation names the real source of the covenant curse with precision: abandonment of the commandments, specifically the first commandment, expressed through Baal worship. Jesus similarly refuses the establishment&rsquo;s framing: &ldquo;You are wrong, because you know neither the Scriptures nor the power of God&rdquo; (Matt 22:29). The prophet who will not accept the king&rsquo;s narrative is the necessary counterpart to covenant faithfulness.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elijah demands a public assembly at Carmel with all 450 prophets of Baal and 400 prophets of Asherah. The scale of the confrontation is total: the full prophetic apparatus of the apostasy is summoned to a single decisive contest. Carmel — <em>karmel</em>, &ldquo;fruitful garden/vineyard&rdquo; — is the mountain of creation&rsquo;s abundance; the confrontation on the &ldquo;vineyard mountain&rdquo; anticipates the parable of the vineyard tenants (Matt 21:33-41), where the son is sent to the vineyard to receive its fruit and is killed.</p>",
    "20": "<p>All Israel gathers at Carmel. The assembly of the whole people for the decisive verdict on covenant allegiance; the parallel is the universal judgment assembly where every nation stands before the Son of Man (Matt 25:31-32). The Carmel assembly is the OT&rsquo;s most vivid enacted parable of the eschatological gathering for verdict.</p>",
    "21": "<p>&ldquo;How long will you waver between two opinions? If the LORD is God, follow him; but if Baal, then follow him.&rdquo; The Hebrew <em>ʿal šᵉtê hassᵉʿippîm</em> means &ldquo;limping between two forks&rdquo; — the bird&rsquo;s forked-flight image. The either/or of covenant commitment has no middle position. Matt 6:24: &ldquo;No one can serve two masters.&rdquo; Jas 1:8: &ldquo;a double-minded man, unstable in all his ways.&rdquo; Rev 3:16: &ldquo;Because you are lukewarm, and neither hot nor cold, I will spit you out of my mouth.&rdquo; The Carmel challenge is the canonical expression of what Christ demands: undivided allegiance, not syncretism. The silence of the people (&ldquo;And the people did not answer him a word&rdquo;) is the silence of those who have been double-minded so long they cannot choose.</p>",
    "22": "<p>Elijah alone against 450 Baal prophets — the outnumbered prophet as the sign of YHWH&rsquo;s reliance not on numerical advantage but on truth. Matt 10:16: &ldquo;I am sending you out as sheep in the midst of wolves.&rdquo; The early church was always a minority; the apostles faced the Sanhedrin two against the establishment. The prophetic minority is the consistent pattern: Noah, Jeremiah, Elijah, the apostles — YHWH&rsquo;s work is not accomplished by majority vote.</p>",
    "23": "<p>Equal conditions for the contest: two bulls, same preparation, no fire lit by human hands. The contest is designed so that only genuine divine response can decide it. The conditions remove every human variable. Cf. the resurrection: the tomb sealed, guarded, watched — the conditions designed to prevent any natural explanation of what happens next.</p>",
    "24": "<p>&ldquo;The God who answers by fire — he is God.&rdquo; Fire is YHWH&rsquo;s primary theophanic medium: the burning bush (Exod 3:2), the pillar of fire (Exod 13:21), Sinai (Exod 19:18), the glory cloud (Lev 9:24). The test proposes fire as the visible criterion of divine reality. Acts 2:3-4: the Spirit descends at Pentecost &ldquo;as of fire&rdquo; — tongues of fire rest on each disciple, the new covenant&rsquo;s visible sign of YHWH&rsquo;s answer to the sacrifice of Christ. Luke 12:49: &ldquo;I came to cast fire on the earth.&rdquo; The Elijah-fire criterion is fulfilled in the one who &ldquo;baptizes with the Holy Spirit and fire&rdquo; (Matt 3:11).</p>",
    "25": "<p>Elijah gives the Baal prophets first choice and the larger preparation time — magnanimous conditions that underscore the outcome. The generosity of the contest conditions makes the failure of Baal all the more complete: they had every advantage. Cf. the parable of the vineyard laborers (Matt 20:1-16): the master&rsquo;s generosity to his workers reveals not the workers&rsquo; merit but the master&rsquo;s character.</p>",
    "26": "<p>&ldquo;O Baal, answer us!&rdquo; — from morning until noon, leaping about the altar, no voice, no answer, no one attending. The silence of Baal is the silence of non-being. Paul: &ldquo;We know that an idol has no real existence, and that there is no God but one&rdquo; (1 Cor 8:4). The limping dance around the altar — <em>wayᵉpassᵉḥû</em>, the same root as &ldquo;Passover&rdquo; (<em>pesaḥ</em>) — is the perverse liturgy of those who worship what cannot save, performing their rite with no corresponding reality. Christ does not perform rites that produce no divine response; he is himself the divine response.</p>",
    "27": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s noon mockery: &ldquo;Call louder — he is a god! Maybe he is deep in thought, or busy, or traveling. Perhaps he is sleeping and must be awakened.&rdquo; The Hebrew uses standard ANE divine epithets ironically: &ldquo;meditating,&rdquo; &ldquo;wandering,&rdquo; &ldquo;on a journey,&rdquo; &ldquo;sleeping.&rdquo; Each is a normal attribute claimed for pagan deities — Elijah recites them as evidence of Baal&rsquo;s absence. Ps 121:4: &ldquo;He who keeps Israel will neither slumber nor sleep&rdquo; — YHWH is defined precisely by the constant wakefulness Baal lacks. The Incarnate Word slept in the storm (Mark 4:38) — but his sleep was not Baal&rsquo;s absence; when roused he demonstrated sovereignty over the creation Baal could only imitate.</p>",
    "28": "<p>The Baal prophets slash themselves with swords and spears &ldquo;as was their custom.&rdquo; The self-laceration was a ritual attempt to attract divine attention through blood — the god was thought to respond to the worshiper&rsquo;s blood. Lev 19:28 explicitly forbids this: &ldquo;You shall not make any cuts on your body.&rdquo; The contrast with the Carmel sacrifice is total: Elijah will not draw his own blood, but YHWH will consume the sacrifice by fire. Christ does not lacerate himself to attract his Father&rsquo;s attention; his self-offering is not frantic but deliberate — &ldquo;not as I will, but as you will&rdquo; (Matt 26:39).</p>",
    "29": "<p>&ldquo;No voice, no answer, and no one paying attention.&rdquo; The triple negation at the time of the evening offering — the very hour when the Jerusalem altar was supposed to be producing the daily sacrifice — is the complete silence of Baal during the time consecrated to YHWH. The evening offering (3 PM) will be the hour when Elijah&rsquo;s prayer produces fire; it is also the hour of Christ&rsquo;s death (Mark 15:34-37). The silence of Baal at the hour of sacrifice is answered by the fire of YHWH; the apparent silence of God at Calvary is answered by the resurrection.</p>",
    "30": "<p>Elijah repairs the broken-down altar of YHWH at Carmel — the altar had been torn down, presumably during the Baal apostasy. Before the sacrifice can be made, the altar must be restored. Cf. Jesus clearing the temple (Matt 21:12-13) — the preparatory cleansing/restoration that precedes the true sacrifice. The work of restoration is itself an act of prophetic witness: the repaired altar declares that YHWH&rsquo;s place of meeting is being reclaimed before the decisive event.</p>",
    "31": "<p>Twelve stones, one for each tribe of Jacob — &ldquo;to whom the word of the LORD came, saying, &lsquo;Israel shall be your name.&rsquo;&rdquo; Elijah builds an altar that reconstitutes all twelve tribes in a northern kingdom that has been divided for a century. The twelve-stone altar is a prophetic act of eschatological unity: the division of the kingdom is treated as temporary, the covenant unity as permanent. Matt 19:28: &ldquo;You who have followed me will also sit on twelve thrones, judging the twelve tribes of Israel.&rdquo; Rev 21:12: twelve gates named for the twelve tribes. The Carmel altar anticipates the new Jerusalem — a twelve-tribe community gathered before YHWH.</p>",
    "32": "<p>A trench large enough to hold two seahs of seed is dug around the altar — creating the condition for the water pouring that follows. The meticulous preparation of conditions designed to make the miracle more obviously miraculous: when water fills the trench around the saturated sacrifice, the natural explanation of accidental fire becomes impossible. The divine action is designed to be unambiguous. The empty tomb is similarly prepared to be unambiguous: sealed, guarded, witnessed (Matt 27:62-66; 28:1-6).</p>",
    "33": "<p>The sacrifice is arranged; water is poured over it once. Elijah engineers the conditions of maximum impossibility step by step: first the sacrifice laid on the wood, then the water poured once. The deliberate escalation of natural impossibility as the preparation for supernatural action. The deeper pattern: Christ&rsquo;s burial is the saturation of the sacrifice with human finality — &ldquo;it is finished&rdquo; (John 19:30) before the fire falls.</p>",
    "34": "<p>A second pouring, then a third. Three times the water is poured — the sacrifice is saturated, the trench filled. The triple saturation is both practical (removing any doubt) and typological: three is the number of covenantal completeness, the same number as the days before the resurrection. By the third application of impossibility, the stage is set for the fire that transcends it.</p>",
    "35": "<p>The water runs down around the altar and fills the trench — the visual demonstration of complete saturation is now visible to all the people watching. The setup is complete; nothing natural can ignite what follows. The public nature of the impossible conditions is part of the event&rsquo;s theological function: YHWH&rsquo;s acts are performed in the sight of all Israel, not secretly (cf. Acts 26:26: &ldquo;this was not done in a corner&rdquo;).</p>",
    "36": "<p>&ldquo;O LORD, God of Abraham, Isaac, and Israel, let it be known today that you are God in Israel, and that I am your servant.&rdquo; Elijah&rsquo;s prayer at the evening offering hour invokes the patriarchal covenant: YHWH as God of the three founding fathers, his bond to Israel confirmed through them. The prayer asks YHWH to vindicate both himself and his prophet — the two are inseparable in covenantal logic. John 17:1-3: Jesus&rsquo;s high-priestly prayer at the hour of offering uses the same structure: &ldquo;Father, the hour has come. Glorify your Son that the Son may glorify you.&rdquo;</p>",
    "37": "<p>&ldquo;Answer me, O LORD, answer me — that this people may know that you, LORD, are God, and that you have turned their heart back.&rdquo; The double imperative <em>ʿănēnî, ʿănēnî</em> — &ldquo;answer me, answer me&rdquo; — and the covenantal goal: not merely vindication of Elijah but the turning of Israel&rsquo;s heart. Elijah&rsquo;s prayer is missiological — the fire is for Israel&rsquo;s conversion. John 17:21: &ldquo;that the world may believe that you have sent me&rdquo; — the same logic: the visible divine act is for the sake of those who witness it. The apparent success of Carmel (they confess &ldquo;The LORD, he is God&rdquo;) is followed immediately by Jezebel&rsquo;s threat — just as the resurrection is followed by ongoing persecution. Conversion is YHWH&rsquo;s act, not guaranteed by the most dramatic signs.</p>",
    "38": "<p>The fire of YHWH falls and consumes &ldquo;the burnt offering, the wood, the stones, and the dust, and licked up the water in the trench.&rdquo; The divine fire is total: it does not merely light the sacrifice but consumes everything — including the impossible (water). Heb 12:29: &ldquo;our God is a consuming fire&rdquo; — the Carmel fire is the paradigmatic OT event behind this NT description of divine holiness. The consuming fire at Carmel consumed the sacrifice and the impossibility alike; the consuming fire of the final judgment will consume all that is not of God and leave only what is (1 Cor 3:13-15).</p>",
    "39": "<p>All the people fell facedown and cried: &ldquo;The LORD, he is God! The LORD, he is God!&rdquo; — <em>YHWH hûʾ hāʾelōhîm, YHWH hûʾ hāʾelōhîm</em>. The double declaration — the same one heard at Elijah&rsquo;s death-prayer in 2 Kgs 2; the cry of the people at the consuming fire. Phil 2:10-11: &ldquo;at the name of Jesus every knee should bow... and every tongue confess that Jesus Christ is Lord.&rdquo; The Carmel confession is the OT type of the universal confession that will close history: not compelled by argument but by the visible fire of divine action. The people &ldquo;saw&rdquo; and &ldquo;fell facedown&rdquo; — the sequence of sight producing prostration is the eschatological pattern.</p>",
    "40": "<p>Elijah commands: &ldquo;Seize the prophets of Baal — do not let one of them escape.&rdquo; He brings them to the Kishon brook and slaughters them there — executing the <em>ḥerem</em> against the leaders of apostasy. The prophets of Baal are killed, not merely dispersed. The eschatological version: Rev 19:20-21, where the false prophet is seized and cast into the lake of fire and the kings of the earth who followed him are slain by the sword from the rider&rsquo;s mouth. The pattern of the decisive post-victory judgment on the agents of apostasy.</p>",
    "41": "<p>&ldquo;There is the sound of heavy rain.&rdquo; Elijah hears the rain before any cloud has appeared — prophetic perception of the divine action that has not yet become visible. Heb 11:1: &ldquo;faith is the assurance of things hoped for, the conviction of things not seen.&rdquo; The prophet acts on the certainty of what YHWH has promised; the sound he hears in the spirit is more real than the drought that remains visible. Jesus: &ldquo;when you pray, believe that you have received it, and it will be yours&rdquo; (Mark 11:24).</p>",
    "42": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s posture of intercession — crouched down on the ground, face between his knees — is the bodily expression of intense, persistent prayer. Jas 5:17-18 calls this &ldquo;fervent prayer&rdquo; (<em>proseuchē proseucho</em> — &ldquo;he prayed with prayer,&rdquo; a Hebraism for intense, repeated petition). Rom 8:26: &ldquo;the Spirit intercedes for us with groanings too deep for words.&rdquo; Elijah&rsquo;s posture externalizes the inward intensity that Paul describes as too deep for articulation.</p>",
    "43": "<p>Six times the servant looks and sees nothing — the prophet sends him back six times to watch without giving up. The seventh time will bring the sign. The persistence of prophetic intercession in the face of non-response mirrors Jesus&rsquo;s parable of the persistent widow (Luke 18:1-8): &ldquo;he told them a parable to the effect that they ought always to pray and not lose heart.&rdquo; The six times of nothing are not failures but the conditions that make the seventh significant.</p>",
    "44": "<p>&ldquo;A small cloud, about the size of a man&rsquo;s hand, is rising from the sea.&rdquo; The tiny sign of the coming deluge. The smallest possible beginning that contains within it the largest possible result. Matt 13:31-32: the mustard seed, &ldquo;the smallest of all seeds,&rdquo; becomes the largest tree. The kingdom of God begins as a small cloud from the sea — the Incarnation, the tiny stable in Bethlehem — and grows to cover the earth. Elijah&rsquo;s immediate, unhesitating response to the small cloud (&ldquo;Go, say to Ahab, Prepare your chariot and go down, that the rain may not stop you&rdquo;) models the response the small beginnings of the kingdom require: total commitment on minimal evidence.</p>",
    "45": "<p>The sky darkens, the wind rises, the great rain falls. The covenant blessing — rain on the covenanted land (Deut 11:14; 28:12) — is restored in a moment after three years of absence. The instantaneous reversal of covenant curse to covenant blessing is the OT&rsquo;s enacted parable of the eschatological restoration. 2 Cor 6:2: &ldquo;Behold, now is the favorable time; behold, now is the day of salvation&rdquo; — the day when the long drought of alienation is ended by the word of God.</p>",
    "46": "<p>&ldquo;The power of the LORD came on Elijah&rdquo; — <em>yaḏ YHWH</em>, &ldquo;the hand of YHWH&rdquo; — and he ran ahead of Ahab&rsquo;s chariot all the way to Jezreel. The &ldquo;hand of YHWH&rdquo; is the OT&rsquo;s term for the Spirit&rsquo;s empowering of the prophet for supernatural action (also Ezek 1:3; 3:14, 22; 8:1). The same empowering that will come on the disciples at Pentecost: &ldquo;you will receive power when the Holy Spirit has come upon you&rdquo; (Acts 1:8). Elijah&rsquo;s Spirit-empowered run is a type of the Spirit-empowered mission of the church: the divine energy that enables what human capacity cannot accomplish.</p>"
  },
  "19": {
    "1": "<p>Ahab reports to Jezebel &ldquo;everything Elijah had done and how he had killed all the prophets with the sword.&rdquo; The great Carmel victory is immediately followed by the counter-mobilization of the opposing power. The pattern of apostolic ministry: every advance of the gospel is followed by organized opposition (Acts 4:1-3; 8:1-3; 13:50). The fire of Carmel did not convert Jezebel — the hardening of those who resist is accelerated by the displays that convert others (2 Cor 2:15-16: &ldquo;to one a fragrance from death to death, to the other a fragrance from life to life&rdquo;).</p>",
    "2": "<p>Jezebel&rsquo;s oath: &ldquo;May the gods deal with me, however severely, if by tomorrow at this time I do not make your life as the life of one of them.&rdquo; The death threat against the prophet from the wielder of state religious power. John 16:2: &ldquo;the hour is coming when whoever kills you will think he is offering service to God.&rdquo; Jezebel&rsquo;s threat against Elijah is the archetype of every threat against the prophetic witness — always dressed in religious language, always against the one who most faithfully represents YHWH&rsquo;s claims.</p>",
    "3": "<p>Elijah saw and he fled for his life. The prophet who had stood alone against 450 prophets and a hostile king collapses before a single woman&rsquo;s threat. The humanity of the prophet is not hidden in the narrative: the same man who prayed fire from heaven is running in terror. Peter after the crucifixion (John 20:19); the disciples who scattered at Gethsemane (Mark 14:50). The contrast is not with weakness but with the divine sustainer: YHWH does not abandon Elijah in his flight any more than he abandons the disciples in theirs. The beersheba detail — he leaves the northern kingdom entirely, crosses Judah, and goes to the border of the wilderness — measures the extent of his flight.</p>",
    "4": "<p>&ldquo;It is enough; now, O LORD, take away my life, for I am no better than my fathers.&rdquo; The prophet&rsquo;s despair under the juniper tree (<em>rotem</em>) — alone, exhausted, asking for death. The comparison to &ldquo;my fathers&rdquo; reveals the standard he has failed to reach in his own estimation. The NT parallel is Gethsemane: Jesus also asks for the cup to be removed (&ldquo;if it be possible, let this cup pass from me,&rdquo; Matt 26:39) — but the difference is decisive. Elijah asks for death and withdrawal; Jesus accepts death and advances. The prophet&rsquo;s despair contrasts with the Son&rsquo;s surrender: &ldquo;not as I will, but as you will.&rdquo; Both express human extremity before divine demand; only one achieves perfect obedience through it.</p>",
    "5": "<p>An angel touches Elijah and says &ldquo;Arise and eat.&rdquo; The divine provision at the moment of deepest human exhaustion — not a rebuke but a touch and a meal. Matt 4:11: &ldquo;angels came and were ministering to him&rdquo; (Jesus after the forty-day temptation). Both Elijah and Jesus receive angelic provision in the wilderness after the most intense spiritual contest. The pattern: the divine Father does not abandon the servant in extremity but provides exactly what is needed for the journey. The touch — <em>wayyigga‛</em> — is the same word used for healing touch; the angel&rsquo;s contact is restorative.</p>",
    "6": "<p>Bread baked on hot coals and a jar of water — the simplest possible provision. Not abundance but sufficiency; the exact supply for the exact need. The Lord&rsquo;s Prayer: &ldquo;give us this day our daily bread&rdquo; — not a feast but the bread for today&rsquo;s journey. The provision anticipates the pattern of the wilderness manna: daily, precise, from above. Jesus feeds the 5,000 with exactly enough (John 6:12: &ldquo;gather up the leftover fragments&rdquo;) — YHWH&rsquo;s provision is neither deficient nor wasteful.</p>",
    "7": "<p>The angel comes back a second time: &ldquo;Arise and eat, for the journey is too far for you.&rdquo; The divine awareness that what is required exceeds human capacity; the provision is calibrated to the journey ahead, not the journey past. Rom 8:26: &ldquo;the Spirit helps us in our weakness... the Spirit himself intercedes for us.&rdquo; The Father knows the journey is too long; the provision is not merely comfort but equipment. The double visitation — twice the angel comes — echoes the double provision of manna (Exod 16:22-26) on the day before the Sabbath: extra provision for what lies ahead.</p>",
    "8": "<p>&ldquo;He arose and ate and drank, and in the strength of that food he traveled forty days and forty nights until he reached Horeb, the mountain of God.&rdquo; The explicit Moses typology: Exod 24:18; 34:28 — Moses on Sinai/Horeb for forty days and forty nights without eating or drinking. Elijah&rsquo;s forty-day journey on the strength of the angelic food is the inverse: the food provided is sufficient for forty days. Matt 4:2: Jesus fasts forty days and forty nights in the wilderness — the Moses/Elijah typology recapitulated in the one whom both Moses and Elijah will attend at the Transfiguration (Matt 17:3). Horeb is Sinai, the mountain of the original covenant: Elijah is led by divine provision to the place of the law&rsquo;s giving to renew the broken covenant. Jesus is the prophet like Moses (Deut 18:15) and greater than Elijah, who goes not to Horeb but through death to the new covenant sealed in his blood.</p>",
    "9": "<p>&ldquo;What are you doing here, Elijah?&rdquo; — the divine question that opens the encounter in the cave at Horeb. The interrogative is not condemnation but the divine invitation to honest account: &ldquo;Tell me why you are here.&rdquo; Gen 3:9: &ldquo;Adam, where are you?&rdquo; — the same divine question that opens encounter after flight. YHWH does not surprise the fleeing prophet with judgment but with a question that creates space for lament. The pastoral pattern: before commission comes the question that hears the servant&rsquo;s state. John 21:15-17: Jesus asks Peter three times, &ldquo;Do you love me?&rdquo; — opening the restoration by first hearing the one who denied him.</p>",
    "10": "<p>Elijah&rsquo;s complaint: &ldquo;I have been utterly zealous for the LORD, the God of hosts. The people of Israel have abandoned your covenant, thrown down your altars, and killed your prophets with the sword, and I alone am left, and they seek my life.&rdquo; The prophet&rsquo;s self-report is factually accurate but perspectivally incomplete: he has not counted the 7,000. The gap between the prophet&rsquo;s subjective experience of total isolation and the divine reality of the preserved remnant is always larger than the prophet can perceive from within the crisis. The disciples after the crucifixion shared this sense of being &ldquo;the only ones left&rdquo; (Luke 24:21: &ldquo;we had hoped that he was the one to redeem Israel&rdquo;). The divine answer to prophetic despair does not rebuke the feeling but reveals the larger reality the feeling obscured.</p>",
    "11": "<p>&ldquo;Go out and stand on the mountain before the LORD.&rdquo; Wind, earthquake, fire — the classic Sinai theophanic sequence (Exod 19:16-18) — but &ldquo;the LORD was not in the wind... the LORD was not in the earthquake... the LORD was not in the fire.&rdquo; The decisive theological revision of Sinai: YHWH is not identified with his most terrifying manifestations. The theophanic signs are real but they are not YHWH&rsquo;s self-disclosure; they prepare for something quieter. The Incarnation is the ultimate expression of this pattern: God enters the world not through earthquake and cosmic fire but through a human birth, unheralded by any theophany visible to the world. &ldquo;He had no form or majesty that we should look at him&rdquo; (Isa 53:2) — the Incarnate Word passes by in hiddenness, as YHWH passed by Elijah.</p>",
    "12": "<p>&ldquo;After the earthquake a fire — but the LORD was not in the fire. And after the fire a still, small voice&rdquo; — <em>qôl dᵉmāmāh daqqāh</em>, &ldquo;the sound of thin silence,&rdquo; or &ldquo;the voice of soft stillness.&rdquo; The most powerful theophanic medium is paradoxically the least dramatic. The Incarnation is this principle made flesh: the eternal Word enters the world not as fire and earthquake but as an infant in a feeding trough. &ldquo;He emptied himself, taking the form of a servant&rdquo; (Phil 2:7) — the kenōsis is the supreme <em>qôl dᵉmāmāh daqqāh</em>. The pattern governs all of Christ&rsquo;s ministry: he heals quietly, commands silence, withdraws from crowds, speaks in parables that require ears to hear. The divine word comes not in spectacular coercion but in the gentle call that can be refused — and therefore, when received, changes everything.</p>",
    "13": "<p>Elijah wraps his face in his cloak and stands at the cave entrance — the echo of Moses hiding his face from the burning bush (Exod 3:6) and before the glory of YHWH (Exod 34:8). The posture of creaturely reverence before the divine presence: the prophet cannot look directly at YHWH&rsquo;s self-disclosure; he must be veiled. 2 Cor 3:13-18: the veil of Moses, and its removal in Christ — &ldquo;we all, with unveiled face, beholding the glory of the Lord, are being transformed&rdquo; (v18). The difference between Elijah&rsquo;s veiled encounter at Horeb and the believer&rsquo;s unveiled encounter with the glory of God in the face of Jesus Christ (2 Cor 4:6) marks the distance between old covenant mediation and new covenant access.</p>",
    "14": "<p>Elijah repeats his complaint word for word (same as v10). YHWH does not rebuke the repetition; he hears the prophet&rsquo;s self-report a second time and then acts. The pastoral significance: YHWH receives the same lament twice before moving to commission. He does not say &ldquo;you already told me this.&rdquo; The divine patience with human repetition is itself a revelation of character. John 21:15-17: Jesus asks Peter three times, each time receiving Peter&rsquo;s repeated &ldquo;yes.&rdquo; The repetition in prophetic encounter is the form that healing takes: YHWH re-receives the broken state before re-issuing the call.</p>",
    "15": "<p>&ldquo;Go, return on your way to the wilderness of Damascus.&rdquo; The response to Elijah&rsquo;s despair is not retirement but re-commission: go back, anoint Hazael, anoint Jehu, anoint Elisha. YHWH&rsquo;s answer to the prophet&rsquo;s request for death is three more commissions. The sovereign use of instruments beyond the prophet&rsquo;s horizon — Hazael, a Syrian king; Jehu, an Israelite commander — demonstrates that YHWH&rsquo;s purposes are not limited to the prophet who can see them. Hazael as a Gentile king anointed by prophetic word points to YHWH&rsquo;s sovereignty over all nations (Jer 27:5-7); his anointing by Israel&rsquo;s prophet is a type of the commissioning of Gentile rulers for divine purposes that Paul describes in Rom 13:1.</p>",
    "16": "<p>Elisha son of Shaphat from Abel-meholah to be prophet in Elijah&rsquo;s place. The prophetic succession is established by divine designation, not human appointment. But Elisha&rsquo;s commission &ldquo;in your place&rdquo; marks a fundamental difference from Christ&rsquo;s succession: Jesus is not succeeded. &ldquo;I will be with you always, to the end of the age&rdquo; (Matt 28:20) — the one who comes after Elijah has no &ldquo;in your place&rdquo; because his presence is permanent, his priesthood &ldquo;inviolable&rdquo; (Heb 7:24). Elisha succeeds Elijah; the Spirit of Jesus succeeds nothing — he remains.</p>",
    "17": "<p>&ldquo;Whoever escapes the sword of Hazael, Jehu will kill; and whoever escapes the sword of Jehu, Elisha will kill.&rdquo; The layered, sequential judgment of YHWH through multiple human instruments — a Syrian king, an Israelite military commander, and a prophet — exhausts every avenue of escape for the apostate house of Ahab. The divine patience that uses multiple rounds of correction before the final accounting. The eschatological pattern: Rev 6&rsquo;s sequential seals, trumpets, and bowls of divine judgment are the apocalyptic version of this layered structure — YHWH&rsquo;s judgment is thorough, not impulsive.</p>",
    "19": "<p>Elijah finds Elisha plowing with twelve yoke of oxen — the future prophet at work in an ordinary agricultural task. Elijah passes by and throws his cloak (<em>ʾadderet</em>) over him — the same cloak that will later divide the Jordan (2 Kgs 2:8, 13-14) and become the sign of prophetic succession. The cloak as instrument of calling: no words are spoken in the text; the act of covering communicates the commission. Matt 4:18-20: Jesus calls his first disciples from their nets — the same pattern of divine calling that interrupts ordinary work without elaborate explanation. The commission is in the act, not the argument.</p>",
    "20": "<p>&ldquo;Let me kiss my father and mother goodbye, and then I will follow you.&rdquo; The identical request appears in Luke 9:61 — &ldquo;Lord, I will follow you, but let me first say farewell to those at home&rdquo; — and Jesus refuses it: &ldquo;No one who puts his hand to the plow and looks back is fit for the kingdom of God&rdquo; (Luke 9:62). Elijah allows the farewell; Jesus does not. The escalation from prophet to Christ in the demands of discipleship: the new covenant mission is more urgent, its cost higher, its break with the old life more complete than the prophetic call. Jesus&rsquo;s use of the plow image (&ldquo;hand to the plow&rdquo;) deliberately echoes the Elisha scene — the one who left his plow to follow Elijah is now the standard for what following Jesus requires and exceeds.</p>",
    "21": "<p>Elisha slaughters the oxen and boils their flesh using the wooden plow-yokes as fuel — the burning of the instruments of his former life. The plow is destroyed; the oxen are consumed; the feast for his people follows. The act of irrevocable commitment: by destroying his tools and eating his animals, Elisha closes the door on return to agriculture. Phil 3:7-8: &ldquo;whatever gain I had, I counted as loss for the sake of Christ... I have suffered the loss of all things and count them as rubbish, in order that I may gain Christ.&rdquo; The burning plow is the OT form of Paul&rsquo;s &ldquo;counting as loss&rdquo; — the voluntary, visible, irreversible abandonment of the former life as the condition of following the prophet.</p>"
  }
}

